    <type>Spacecraft</type>
    <naif_host_id>PVO</naif_host_id>
    <description>The Pioneer Venus Multiprobe mission included four atmospheric entry probes that studied Venus's atmosphere and surface. The mission featured three identical small probes (North, Night, and Day) released from a spacecraft bus on November 20, 1978, with their atmospheric entries occurring on December 9, 1978. The probes collected data on atmospheric composition, circulation patterns, clouds, and energy exchange, while a sister mission, the Pioneer Venus Orbiter, provided support through simultaneous measurements. Each probe had a mass of 90 kg, a spherical pressure vessel with scientific instruments, and employed a titanium heat shield. The North Probe successfully entered the atmosphere, transmitting data until its impact on the surface of Venus. The total cost of the mission was $83 million.</description>
